Calculation of surface tension of salt solutions: effective polarizability of solvated ions
Robert A. Stairs

Can. J. Chem. Downloaded from cdnsciencepub.com by UNIVERSITY OF MASSACHUSETTS LIBRARY on 03/03/22 For personal use only.

Abstract: The Onsager-Samaras version of Wagner's theory of surface tension of solutions of 1:1 salts has been modified to include ion-induced dipole terms in the image potential. Effective solvated ionic polarizabilities are used, which are large and negative owing to local dielectric saturation around the ions. The modified theory agrees with the order of magnitude of the variation among various alkali halides (e.g., A o for 0.1 molar aqueous KI is about 70% of the corresponding value for KCI). Polarizabilities were estimated from Hasted's dielectric decrements.
Key I.I'O~C/s.Yur:face tension. salt solutions, symmetric electrolytes, effective polarirability, theory

