By itself, this term, which is attractive if a is positive, causes the potential energy of an ion at the surface to be large and negative, so the area l- again becomes infinite and positive. Since the effective polarizability of a solvated ion is always negative, however (see below), the area remains finite and negative. A term representing the (induced) dipoledipole potential was originally added. Since the range of the corresponding force is short, it serves only to reduce further the concentration very close to the surface, from which the solute is nearly totally excluded by the other forces. Its effect is therefore negligible.
