Polarizability We have not yet discussed the choice of the values for the polarizabilities of the solvated ions. Hasted, Ritson, and Collie (19) have considered this problem and have made (very difficult!) measurements of the effect of dissolved salts on the permittivity of water, in the limit of low frequency, expressing the results in the form:
The factor 6 is called the "dielectric decrement," for the effect of the ions is to strongly orient the solvent molecules in their vicinity, much reducing their freedom to respond to an applied field, and so decreasing E below the solvent value, E ~ T. he measurements were made at concentrations from 0.5 molar upwards and extrapolated to zero concentration. The authors make a somewhat arbitrary division of the observed values between cation and anion, and report for univalent ions: H+ -17, Li+ -1 1, Na+ -8, K+ -8, Rb+ -7, F- -5, C1-3, I- -7, and OH- -13 (all k0.5) L mol-1. The relative magnitudes accord more or less with expectation, those for the cations diminishing as the radius increases, a trend that seems to be followed also by fluoride and chloride. Iodide
- seems to be anomalous. That H+ and OH- show the largest
effects in their respective series is not surprising, considering their unusually large mobilities in water and their special structural relation to that solvent.
